No box or ppwk, but very easy to breakdown like a piston driven AR-15.  Also, not sure where the rail sections are, but I'm sure you could order them pretty cheap, if wanting to attach gizmos and gadgetry to the rifle.  Again, this is the Gen 2 rifle, so none of the issues the Gen 1 had, you can use all std. AK-47 mags including steel mags.  There is a small mark on left side of receiver, otherwise, perfect.  The only place I found that has these in stock is selling them for $1,300 + any tax and/or shipping.

$1,100 FIRM in cash or better in trade.

Trades considered:

About the only want I can think of right now is a Sig P938.  I've seen a couple models that sell new in the low $500's, so one of those would be perfect.  Let me know what you are adding to the deal in cash or another firearm etc.

Semi-auto rifles, AR-15 & variants, AR-10 & variants, AK-47 & variants(Saiga, VEPR, PSL) in 7.62x39, .308/7.62x51 and 7.62x54.

Quality AR-15 & AR-10 lowers, uppers, stripped, assembled, rails, BCG, nice trigger groups etc. 

Pistols in 9mm and .45ACP mainly, but may consider other calibers, revolvers in .357 mag and .44 mag mainly.    

Less interested in, but may consider bolt-actions, lever guns(.357 & .44 mag mainly) and shotguns(prefer Mossberg 590, 590A1 models & 930 SPX, others?), depending on the deal and values etc.  

Silver Eagles and 1oz. silver bars or rounds, maybe gold in grams, I check prices daily.

Maybe quality optics like Vortex or others, mid level models, not cheap, but not crazy expensive either, 4-16x or maybe greater power range.  Maybe ammo to help make a deal happen in 9mm, .45ACP, .357 Sig, .357 & .44 Mag, .22lr, .223/5.56, 7.62x39, .308/7.62x51, 7.62x54 tins, .300 Win Mag, 12ga. "00","000" buckshot and slugs.

title: For Sale:  1940 High Standard Model HD with box - SOLD!!!!
postcontent:
Hard-to-find model in mint condition. Gun and box serial numbers match. there are 3 boxes of period correct ammo that came with it, 2 full and the last missing 19 rounds.
This model has history:
In 1960,  US Air Force Lt. Gary Powers was somewhere that never existed in a plane that wasn’t on the official record. His plane, the U-2 recon aircraft was shot down over the Ural mountain city of Sverdlovsk in the Soviet Union.  Placed on public trial in Moscow, Powers admitted that his craft was in fact a CIA operated top-secret spy plane. In the trial, the Soviets produced a silenced Hi-Standard model USA-HD caliber .22LR, serial number 120046. The serial number is not listed in High Standard’s books and it has commonly been surmised that it was sold on spec to the CIA for operatives in the 1950s. Others were reportedly made without any markings whatsoever to be ‘sterile’ and thus deniable.

I submitted pics to John Stimson for his opinion. He stated these are far more scarce than thought based on production numbers. Especially in the original box with accessories. 

I dug into his website and found that he had listed serial number 64455 as being manufactured on 9/14/1940. This is 64457.

title: For Sale:  Marlin MR-7 30-06 Hard to find collectible excellent shooting rifle
postcontent: Marlin MR-7 Bolt action rifle in .30-06 manufactured in 1996. Marlin only made the MR-7 from 1996-1999. It was chambered in .25-06, .270, .280, and .30-06. It features a 3-position safety, a bolt face encircled by three rings of 4140 steel, a shrouded striker and high-visibility cocking indicator. It has an adjustable 3-6 lb trigger, A forged, machined and heat-treated receiver and an extra-strong bolt lockup. The Mr-7 has a hinged floorplate with a removable yet securely mounted 4-shot box magazine. It has a 22" barrel with 6-groove precision rifling and a recessed muzzle. It also has a classically configured, cut-checkered American walnut stock. This rifle is in Excellent condition, metal finish rates at 95%. The wood has some small scratches and dents which I have shown the worst of and most visible in the photos. The bore is perfect. You dont see these available on the market anymore as they have become a collector type niche, and at time of posting this is the only one listed on Gunbroker for sale. Marlin mimicked many legendary bolt action with this model, the safety of a Winchester Model 70 the locking lug and positive cartridge engagement of the Remington 700, the bolt handle design of the Ruger M77 and the box magazine of a Browning A-bolt, and they actually faced a few lawsuits I believe for some of these infringements which was one of the reasons the production run was so limited. I have owned this rifle since new, and it has been well taken care of and has not been shot for the last 6 years. The few marks on the stock came when I loaned it to a friend of mine for deer hunting one season, and after he returned it with the shown scratches I retired it from anything but occasional admiring.This also comes with Weaver bases for a scope. More photos available
